= A Significant Space
- The evolution of a *coelom* (fluid-filled space within the mesoderm) was a major step in the evolution of larger and more complex forms.
- Unlike pseudocoelomates where organs lie loose, in coelomates, organs are suspended by *mesenteries* (mesodermal membranes).
- Mesenteries provide ideal locations for blood vessel networks and allow the alimentary canal to become more muscular and specialized without interfering with other organs.
- In many coelomates, the coelom serves as a *hydrostatic skeleton*, but in molluscs, the heavy shell restricts this function, and the coelom is relatively small.

= Molluscs
- *Mollusca* is one of the largest animal phyla, with over 90,000 living species.
- They are *coelomate lophotrochozoan protostomes* with spiral mosaic cleavage and schizocoelous coelom formation.
- The ancestral larval stage is a *trochophore*.
- The group is extremely diverse, ranging from microscopic forms to giant squids (*Architeuthis*).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-1").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-1").caption)
- Molluscs are found in nearly all habitats: marine (tropics to polar, surface to abyss), freshwater, and terrestrial (snails and slugs).
- Humans exploit molluscs for food, pearls, and buttons, but some are pests (e.g., shipworms, garden snails, intermediate hosts for parasites).
- The phylum includes several classes with varying degrees of diversity and distinct synapomorphies, as shown in the cladogram.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-2").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-2").caption)

= Form and Function
- The generalized mollusc body plan consists of two main portions: the *head-foot* (active area) and the *visceral mass* (metabolic area).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-3").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-3").caption)
- Two folds of skin form the *mantle*, which encloses the *mantle cavity* containing gills (*ctenidia*) or lungs and secretes the *shell*.

== Head-Foot
- Most molluscs have a well-developed head with mouth and sensory organs.
- *Radula*: A rasping, protrusible, tonguelike organ found in all molluscs except bivalves and most solenogasters.
  - It consists of a ribbonlike membrane with rows of tiny teeth pointing backward.
  - It moves over a supporting cartilage called the *odontophore*.
  - Used for feeding (scraping, piercing, tearing, cutting) and conveying food to the digestive tract.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-4").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-4").caption)
- *Foot*: The chief locomotor organ, usually ventral and solelike.
  - Adapted for creeping, attachment (limpets), burrowing (bivalves), or jet propulsion (cephalopods).
  - Can be extended hydraulically by engorgement with blood.

== Visceral Mass
- *Mantle and Mantle Cavity*:
  - The mantle protects soft parts and creates the mantle cavity.
  - The mantle cavity houses respiratory organs (gills/lungs) and receives products from digestive, excretory, and reproductive systems.
  - In aquatic forms, water currents bring oxygen/food and flush out wastes.
  - *Ctenidium* (gill): Consists of a central axis with leaf-like filaments. Blood flow is opposite to water flow (*countercurrent exchange*).
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-5").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-5").caption)
- *Shell*: Secreted by the mantle and typically has three layers:
  - *Periostracum*: Outer organic layer (conchiolin), protects against erosion.
  - *Prismatic layer*: Middle layer of densely packed calcium carbonate prisms.
  - *Nacreous layer*: Inner layer, secreted continuously, forming the iridescent "mother-of-pearl".
  - Pearls are formed when a foreign object becomes lodged between the shell and mantle and is covered with nacre.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-6").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-6").caption)

== Internal Structure and Function
- *Circulatory System*: Open circulatory system (except cephalopods) with a pumping heart, vessels, and blood sinuses. Less efficient than closed systems.
- *Excretion*: Most have a pair of kidneys (*metanephridia*) opening into the coelom via a *nephrostome*.
- *Nervous System*: Paired ganglia (cerebral, pleural, pedal, visceral) with nerve cords.
- *Reproduction*:
  - Most are dioecious; some hermaphroditic.
  - *Trochophore* larva: Free-swimming, top-shaped larva with a circlet of cilia (*prototroch*); ancestral for molluscs and annelids.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-7").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-7").caption)
  - *Veliger* larva: A uniquely molluscan larval stage with the beginnings of a foot, shell, and mantle, and ciliated velar lobes for swimming.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-8").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-8").caption)

= Classes of Molluscs

== Class Caudofoveata
- Wormlike, marine, burrowing animals.
- Lack a shell but have calcareous scales/spicules.
- Have an oral shield and a radula.

== Class Solenogastres
- Wormlike, marine, bottom-dwellers (often feed on cnidarians).
- Usually lack radula and gills.
- Foot is represented by a midventral pedal groove.

== Class Monoplacophora
- Thought extinct until discovery of *_Neopilina_* in 1952.
- Small, with a single low, rounded shell and creeping foot.
- Exhibit *pseudometamerism*: serial repetition of organs (gills, muscles, nephridia).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-9").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-9").caption)

== Class Polyplacophora: Chitons
- Dorsoventrally flattened with a convex dorsal surface bearing *seven or eight articulating limy plates*.
- Head and sensory organs reduced; *esthetes* (photosensitive structures) pierce the plates.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-10").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-10").caption)
- Prefer rocky intertidal surfaces; cling tightly with a broad foot.
- Mantle forms a girdle around the plates.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-11").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-11").caption)
- Gills are numerous and suspended in the mantle grooves along the sides of the foot.

== Class Scaphopoda
- *Tusk shells* or tooth shells.
- Benthic marine; slender body covered by a mantle and a tubular shell open at both ends.
- Foot protrudes through the larger end to burrow.
- Gills are absent; gas exchange occurs in the mantle.
- Food is caught by *captacula* (ciliated, adhesive tentacles).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-12").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-12").caption)

== Class Gastropoda
- Largest and most diverse class (snails, limpets, slugs, nudibranchs, etc.).
- Shell, when present, is *univalve* (one piece), coiled or uncoiled.
- Shell features: *apex*, *whorls*, *columella* (central axis), *aperture*, *operculum* (cover).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-13").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-13").caption)

=== Torsion
- *Torsion* is a developmental process where the visceral mass rotates 180 degrees counterclockwise relative to the head.
- Moves the anus and mantle cavity to the anterior position, above the head.
- *Ontogenetic torsion*: The developmental sequence.
- *Evolutionary torsion*: The evolutionary history.
- Advantages: Head can be withdrawn into shell; sensory organs in mantle cavity face forward.
- Disadvantage: *Fouling* (wastes washing back over gills and head).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-14").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-14").caption)

=== Coiling
- *Coiling* is the spiral winding of the shell and visceral mass (separate from torsion).
- Evolution from *planospiral* (all whorls in one plane) to *conispiral* (whorls to the side).
- Conispiral shape caused unbalance, solved by shifting shell upward and posteriorly.
- This shift pressed on the right side of the mantle cavity, leading to the loss of the right gill, auricle, and kidney (*bilateral asymmetry*).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-15").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-15").caption)

=== Feeding Habits
- Varied feeding: herbivorous grazers (abalone), scavengers, carnivores, borers, ciliary feeders.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-16").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-16").caption)
- *_Conus_* snails use a modified radula tooth as a harpoon with toxic venom (*conotoxins*) to capture prey.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-17").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-17").caption)

=== Internal Form and Function
- Respiration: Typically by a *ctenidium* in the mantle cavity.
- To avoid fouling, water often enters the left side and exits the right side (carrying wastes).
- Evolution of gills: Loss of right gill and half of the left gill filaments to improve efficiency.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-18").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-18").caption)
- *Pulmonates* lack gills; the vascularized mantle wall functions as a *lung*, opening via a *pneumostome*.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-19").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-19").caption)
- Reproduction: Monoecious or dioecious; internal fertilization in most; eggs often laid in capsules.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-20").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-20").caption)

=== Major Groups
- *Prosobranchs*: Mostly marine; mantle cavity anterior; gills in front of heart; operculum usually present. Examples: abalones, whelks, periwinkles.
  - Some have holes in the shell for excurrent water (e.g., keyhole limpets) to avoid fouling.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-21").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-21").caption)
- *Opisthobranchs*: Marine (sea slugs, sea hares, nudibranchs); show partial or complete *detorsion* (anus to right or posterior); shell reduced or absent.
  - *Sea hares* (*_Aplysia_*) have large parapodia and release protective ink.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-22").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-22").caption)
  - *Nudibranchs* are carnivorous, often brightly colored, and may use hijacked nematocysts from cnidarian prey for defense.
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-23").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-23").caption)
- *Pulmonates*: Land and freshwater snails/slugs; mantle cavity modified into a lung; monoecious.
  - Land forms have two pairs of tentacles (posterior pair bears eyes).
  - #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-24").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-24").caption)

== Class Bivalvia (Pelecypoda)
- Mussels, clams, scallops, oysters, shipworms.
- Two shells (*valves*) held by a hinge ligament; no head or radula; mostly filter feeders.
- Invasive species like the *zebra mussel* (*_Dreissena polymorpha_*) cause significant ecological and economic damage.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-25").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-25").caption)

=== Form and Function
- *Shell*: Valves drawn together by *adductor muscles* working against the hinge ligament. *Umbo* is the oldest part.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-26").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-26").caption)
- *Body*: Visceral mass suspended dorsally; muscular foot attached anteroventrally; ctenidia hang on each side.
- *Gills*: Modified for filter feeding. Filaments lengthened and folded to form *lamellae* with water tubes inside.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-27").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-27").caption)
- *Siphons*: Posterior mantle edges modified into incurrent and excurrent siphons for water flow, allowing burrowing.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-28").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-28").caption)
- *Locomotion*: Foot extended, engorged with blood to anchor, then contracted to pull body forward. Scallops swim by clapping valves.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-29").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-29").caption)
- *Internal Structure*: Three-chambered heart; U-shaped kidneys.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-30").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-30").caption)

=== Feeding
- Ciliary currents bring water/food to gills.
- Mucus entangles particles; cilia move mucous masses to food grooves and *labial palps*.
- Palps sort particles and direct food to mouth.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-31").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-31").caption)
- *Shipworms* (*_Teredo_*) burrow in wood using valves as rasps; symbiotic bacteria digest cellulose.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-32").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-32").caption)
- *Giant clams* (*_Tridacna_*) have symbiotic zooxanthellae in mantle tissue.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-33").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-33").caption)
- *Crystalline style*: A gelatinous rod in the stomach that rotates to mix food and release enzymes.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-34").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-34").caption)

=== Reproduction
- Sexes usually separate; external fertilization in marine forms (trochophore, veliger, spat).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-35").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-35").caption)
- Freshwater clams: Internal fertilization; larvae develop into *glochidia* (parasitic veligers) that attach to fish gills.
- Some mussels have mantle lures to attract host fish.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-36").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-36").caption)

== Class Cephalopoda
- Squids, octopuses, nautiluses, cuttlefish.
- All marine active predators.
- Foot modified into a *funnel* (siphon) and a circle of *arms* or *tentacles*.

=== Shell
- *_Nautilus_*: Coiled shell with gas-filled chambers connected by a *siphuncle* (living tissue cord) for buoyancy regulation.
- *Ammonoids* (extinct): Elaborate chambered shells.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-37").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-37").caption)
- *Cuttlefish*: Internal shell (*cuttlebone*).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-38").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-38").caption)
- *Squid*: Thin internal proteinaceous strip (*pen*).
- *Octopus*: Shell absent.

=== Locomotion and Internal Features
- Swim by jet propulsion (expelling water through funnel).
- *Respiration*: One pair of gills (except _Nautilus_ with two); no cilia; muscular pumping of mantle.
- *Circulation*: Closed circulatory system; *branchial hearts* (accessory hearts) at base of gills increase pressure.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-39").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-39").caption)
- *Nervous System*: Highly developed brain; giant nerve fibers in squids for rapid escape.
- *Senses*: Complex eyes (cornea, lens, retina) similar to vertebrates (*convergent evolution*).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-40").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-40").caption)
- *Communication*: Visual signals using *chromatophores* (pigment cells) for color changes; ink sac for defense.

=== Reproduction
- Sexes separate.
- Males use a modified arm (*hectocotylus*) to transfer spermatophores to the female.
- Direct development (no free-swimming larva).
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-41").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-41").caption)

=== Major Groups
- *Nautiloidea*: _Nautilus_ (2 pairs of gills).
- *Ammonoidea*: Extinct.
- *Coleoidea*: 1 pair of gills.
  - *Sepioidea* (cuttlefish): 8 arms, 2 tentacles.
  - *Teuthida* (squids): 8 arms, 2 tentacles.
  - *Octopoda* (octopuses): 8 arms, no tentacles.

= Phylogeny and Adaptive Diversification
- Molluscs are lophotrochozoan protostomes.
- Relationship with annelids is debated (shared trochophore, but lack of segmentation in ancestral mollusc).
- "Hypothetical Ancestral Mollusc" likely wormlike with dorsal mantle and scales.
- Adaptive radiation driven by mantle and shell modifications.
- #figure(image(images.at("figure-16-42").path, width: 50%), caption: images.at("figure-16-42").caption)
